## 3. Polymorphism

**Definition:** The same method call behaves differently depending on the actual object type at runtime.

### Example 1 — `takeTurn()` on Players
```java
// UnoGame.java — ONE line handles both Human and AI
Player current = state.getCurrentPlayer();
Card played = current.takeTurn(state);
//            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
// If current is HumanPlayer → shows hand, waits for keyboard input
// If current is AIPlayer    → instantly picks using Strategy
// UnoGame never checks "instanceof" — it just calls takeTurn()
```

### Example 2 — `applyEffect()` on Cards
```java
// UnoGame.java — ONE line handles all card types
played.applyEffect(state);
//     ^^^^^^^^^^^
// NumberCard  → state.advanceTurn()
// ActionCard (SKIP)     → state.skipNextPlayer()
// ActionCard (REVERSE)  → state.reverseDirection()
// ActionCard (DRAW_TWO) → state.drawCardsForNext(2) + skip
// WildCard              → asks for color, optionally draws 4
```

### Example 3 — `chooseCard()` on Strategies
```java
// AIPlayer.java — same call, 3 different behaviors
Card chosen = strategy.chooseCard(playable, state);
//            ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
// AggressiveStrategy → picks draw/skip cards first
// DefensiveStrategy  → picks number cards first
// RandomStrategy     → picks randomly
```

### Why This Matters
Without polymorphism, the code would look like this:
```java
// BAD — without polymorphism (do NOT do this)
if (current instanceof HumanPlayer) {
    // 20 lines of human input code
} else if (current instanceof AIPlayer) {
    AIPlayer ai = (AIPlayer) current;
    if (ai.getStrategy() instanceof AggressiveStrategy) {
        // ...
    } else if (ai.getStrategy() instanceof DefensiveStrategy) {
        // ...
    }
}
// Every new player type breaks this block!
```

With polymorphism, it's just:
```java
// GOOD — with polymorphism
Card played = current.takeTurn(state); // one line, always correct
```

